article.description: Marscilla Packer's 3-pointer with 38.4 seconds left helped Ohio State hold off Purdue's frantic second-half comeback as the Buckeyes claimed their first Big Ten tournament title with a 63-60.
article.headline: Buckeyes hold off Purdue, win first Big Ten tourney title
article.linkText: Buckeyes hold off Purdue, win first Big Ten tourney title
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Ohio State coach Jim Foster knew who he wanted shooting for a Big Ten title Monday night -- Marscilla Packer.

She delivered with her usual flair.

With 38.4 seconds left and Ohio State (No. 5 ESPN/USA Today, No. 2 AP) trying to fend off a frenzied second-half rally from Purdue (No. 11 ESPN/USA Today, No. 12 AP), Packer calmly caught the ball on the left wing, squared up and sank a 3-pointer to give Ohio State a 63-60 victory and its first conference tournament title.

"She is one of those shooters, you love them because they have no memory," Foster said. "Packer could miss eight in a row and be convinced she's going to make No. 9."

Fortunately for the Buckeyes (28-2), Packer didn't miss much against the Boilermakers.

She made 6-of-11 shots, including two critical 3s in the final three minutes, and scored 10 of her 15 points in the second half. Packer's presence helped Ohio State balance an offensive attack that had relied primarily on the duo of Brandie Hoskins and two-time conference player of the year Jessica Davenport to build a 17-point lead.

Davenport finished with 17 points and 14 rebounds, while Hoskins added 16 points and four assists. Hoskins was named the tournament's Most Outstanding Player.

Of greater importance to Ohio State was this: By winning its 19th straight game, it clinched the Big Ten's automatic bid to the NCAA Tournament and may have solidified a No. 1 seed.

"I feel like we worked hard all season; whatever the committee decides, they decide," Davenport said. "We stayed focused, we think the Big Ten title helped."

Still, this was not typical Ohio State basketball.

Entering Monday the Buckeyes protected halftime leads like they were guarding Fort Knox, having won 54 of their last 56 such games. And with one of the nation's top defensive teams, a 17-point halftime lead seemed insurmountable -- especially with Purdue shooting just 28.6 percent from the field.

That's when the game turned.

Late in the first half, Purdue's mild-mannered coach, Kristy Curry, lost her cool. She stormed onto the court, pointing and screaming at an official with 1:15 left -- drawing a technical foul. To her players, it was a wakeup call.

"It's all about intensity," Curry said. "We are a tight team and I know they feed off me."

The ploy worked perfectly.

After watching Ohio State use an early 14-4 run to take control and close the half on a 17-4 run that put Purdue in a 36-19 deficit, the Boilermakers responded with a flurry of 3-pointers that quickly got them back into the game.

Suddenly, Katie Gearlds started getting shots, Erin Lawless reasserted herself in the middle and the Boilermakers' outside shots were falling. Lawless finished with 17 points and 10
rebounds, while Gearlds added 14 points.

But it was Sharika Webb that got things stared. She hit back-to-back 3-pointers to ignite the comeback, and when the 20-4 run ended, Purdue had trimmed Ohio State's 39-22 lead to 43-39 with 13:15 left.

Seven minutes later, Lawless hit the first of her two 3s to give the Boilermakers a 53-51 lead. Purdue was 7-for-12 from behind the arc in the second half.

"Whenever we had an open look for a 3-pointer, we knocked it down," Gearlds said. "Whenever we had a possession in the second half, we tried to cut into their lead. We did a good job coming back."

But the Buckeyes righted themselves, too. They tied it when Davenport posted up for a layup and retook the lead when Packer hit a 3 with 2:30 to go. After the two teams traded baskets again, Packer delivered the decisive blow -- a 3-pointer from the wing.

"My first thought was to get the ball inside to Jessica," Packer said. "Purdue wasn't going for my fakes, so I started to shoot and they started to fall. When I got an open look, I shot the ball."

Webb had two chances to tie the game on Purdue's final possession but both were off the mark, and Purdue's quest for its third tourney title in four years finally ended as Foster looked relieved.

"For about a 10-minute blip, there was a little insanity out there," Foster said. "But once we got our legs under us defensively, we got more composed offensively."
